Answer (Q2):

  • Inner join only combined the common data between the two datasets by name & order.
  • Left join brought data in from the left originating from info and filled in NA for values not found in the mammals.info.
  • Right join brought data in from the right originating from info and filled in NA for values for diets which arent present in mammals.info.
  • Anti join only combined data that is not common between both datasets, this presented only the unique species data from mammals.diet.

Compare your outputs - are they all the same? Which one(s) is(are) correct? Below, explain briefly which one(s) give(s) the right answer, and why the wrong ones are wrong. This can/should be a bulleted list.

Answer (Q4):

  • The average presented from dropped_dataset only applies the function mean() to rows that had NO NA values. Therefore, this is innaccurate because it removes animals with recorded brain weights but missing observations in other columns.

  • The average presented from dropped_convseration only applies the function mean() to rows that have NA values in the conservation column. Therefore, this is inaccurate for the same reason specified for dropped_dataset.

  • The average presented from droppped_brain applies to any brain weight observation with a recorded values, thus excluding NA values from this column only. This is one of the CORRECT averages out of the six collected as the only excluded values presented as NA in the brainwt column.

  • The average presented from zero_brain applies to the entire brain weight column, replacing all of the NA values with 0. Therefore, this is incorrect as all the values considered in the calculation werent actually recorded. Thus, the sum is being divided by an inaccurate count making this average invalid.

  • The average presented from the msleep dataset applies to the entire brain weight column, including all of the NA values present here. The resulting average value is incorrect as NA is not a number, it is the absence of a number.

  • The average presented from the msleep dataset with the added na.rm = TRUE argument takes the average of the brain weight column after removing any NA value in this column only. This is one of the CORRECT averages out of the six collected as the only excluded values presented as NA in the brainwt column.

  • Create a new column called glucose_status using the functions mutate() and case_when() that recodes glucose into levels low (<= 70), average (>70, <=120), above-average (>120, <=160), and high (>160). Save your result to a new variable and print the output to confirm. HINT!! You may need to refer back to the intro lab to remind yourself about &.
# wrangle
pima %>%
  mutate(glucose_status = 
           case_when(glucose <= 70 ~ "low",
                     glucose >70 & glucose <= 120 ~ "average",
                     glucose >120 & glucose <=160 ~ "above-average",
                     glucose >160 ~ "high")) -> glucose_scale
